**Introduction**
The discussion relates to navigation from a slot to the contained component and from a component to the containing slot. We may conclude that we only want one of these navigations in the model for interface efficiency. If we conclude on only one then the most efficient is the navigation from a component to the slot(s) that contains it (as when the component is inserted in the slot, the slot does not need to also be updated).

Apologies, the YANG is a bit rough.

**Navigation from component to containing slots**
This is the primary approach in the ivy model today. This is the preferred approach.

                 +--ro parent?
                 |       -> ../../component/component-id

... which is 
                "The identifier of the component that physically
                contains this component."

This navigation is from component to component. As the slot moves to be a subordinate element of a component, we now need to reference a slot in a component. Note that a component may occupy several slots so this should have been a list.

One approach is to keep the reference to a component as is (continuing to support the non-FRU component with no change and then add a reference to the slot(s) as a list element.

A basic method for this is to add a slot list element after parent....

                 +--ro parent?
                 |       -> ../../component/component-id
                 +--ro slot*                                string

It may be relevant to indicate the slot role (whether it is simply occupied or actually connected to the component in it. This is information that can be easily derived from the spec of the slots and the spec of the thing plugged in the slots so we may consider this unnecessary.

We could make the slot list more formally related to the id(s) of the slot(s) in the compoent and provide a "role" statement


         container parent {
           leaf component {
              type leafref {
                path "../../component/component-id";
                require-instance false;
              }
           }
           list slot {
             key "slot-id"
             leaf slot-ref {
               type leafref {
                 path "../../component/component-id/slot/slot-id";
               require-instance false;
               }
               leaf role{
                 type xxx;

                  Will be an enum with connected, occupied, blocked or similar.
               }
             }
           }

**Navigation from slot to contained component**

A slot can only be occupied by one component. The reference is simply to component from a slot list element.

This is a non-preferred orientation of navigation as it is less efficient on the interface. When a component arrives to occupy a slot, the slot needs to be updated with occupancy information (a notification) and the new component needs to be created (a separate notification). 

In the preferred navigation all information is contained in the notification of the component creation including the slot that it occupies. The component with the occupied slot does not need to be updated.

> I think the two-level software-and-patch list is too heavy. How about we use one flat software-version list with an optional “type” (version/release/patch); it keeps the base model small and covers any combination. If a vendor needs a deeper hierarchy, the SW inventory extension can always add parent/child relationships.

I am not sure we have clear definitions to distinguish between version, release, patch and revision ...

Let me try to summarize what I have understood are the possible scenarios, borrowing from Mahesh's example; 

> [mj] In cases such as ours (Arrcus, and I have seen this with other vendors also), the software patch version/rev is part of the software name (or rev) and is not a separate field. For example, if the software version is 8.2.1, the patched version is 8.2.1.P1. Can the description of the software-rev field be relaxed to say that it denotes either the software-rev or a patched version of the image (and remove the software-patch-rev field)?

As far as I have understood, the comment, three implementations are possible on the device

One implementation option is when the device reports three fields:
- SW name: "FOO"
- SW release: "8.2.1"
- SW patch: "P1"

In this case, the network controller has all the information to properly report:

```
{
  "software-rev": [
    {
      "name": "FOO",
      "revision": "8.2.1",
      "patch": [
        {
          "revision": "P1"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

With the alternative proposal from Bo, my understanding is that the network controller could report:

```
{
  "software-rev": [
    {
      "name": "FOO",
      "revision": [
        {
          "version": "8.2.1",
          "type": "revision"
        },
        {
          "version": "P1",
          "type": "patch"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Another implementation option is when the device reports only tow fields:
- SW name: "FOO"
- SW release: "8.2.1.P1"

In this case the network controller has not enough information to split the patch information from the SW patch. The updated descriptions, proposed in PR #135, are intended to allow the network controller to report:

```
{
  "software-rev": [
    {
      "name": "FOO",
      "revision": "8.2.1,P1"
    }
  ]
}
```

It is worth noting that the patch list can be omitted/empty it two cases:
1. when the software revision embeds the software patch information
1. when there is no patch installed

In the [2025-09-17 Base Network Inventory weekly call](https://github.com/ietf-ivy-wg/network-inventory-yang/wiki/minutes-2025-09-17) it was agreed that there is no need to no need for a presence container to avoid ambiguity since this is a vendor choice.

With the alternative proposal from Bo, my understanding is that the network controller could report:

```
{
  "software-rev": [
    {
      "name": "FOO",
      "revision": [
        {
          "version": "8.2.1.P1",
          "type": "revision and patch"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

A third implementation option is when the device reports only one field:
- SW name: "FOO R8.2.1.P1"

In this case the network controller has not enough information to split the release and patch information from the SW name. The updated descriptions, proposed in PR #135, are intended to allow the network controller to report:

```
{
  "software-rev": [
    {
      "name": "FOO R8.2.1.P1"
    }
  ]
}
```

**[2025-10-08 Base Network Inventory weekly call](https://github.com/ietf-ivy-wg/network-inventory-yang/wiki/minutes-2025-10-08)**

The current model in PR #135 allows having more than one patch configured to be active at the same time for the same software module but only one SW revision can be active on the same SW module at the same time.

For example, it is possible to have two patches P1 and P2 applied to the SW module FOO:

```{
  "software-rev": [
    {
      "name": "FOO",
      "revision": "8.2.1",
      "patch": [
        {
          "revision": "P1"
        },
        {
          "revision": "P2"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

The proposal from Bo would allow multiple SW revisions configured to be active on the same SW module. It seems that there are no requirements to allow multiple SW revisions being configured to be active for the same SW module (on the same component) at the same time. Moreover, if multiple SW revisions and patches are listed to, it would not be clear which patches apply to which SW revision.

In order not to delay the WG LC, it has been agreed not to change the model now. However, a WG LC comment can be submitted for further discussion within the IVY WG, if needed.

